slightly better than a tab complete. And then 
now with Claude Opus 4 and Gemini and all that  

187
00:15:24,480 --> 00:15:30,400
kind of stuff, also with deep research, it can go 
off and work for 20 or 30 minutes. So that leash  

188
00:15:30,400 --> 00:15:37,120
is getting longer where you have to intervene.
And I was thinking about this and it reminded  

189
00:15:37,120 --> 00:15:43,680
me of Winnicott, who was a child psychologist. He 
wrote this book called Playing & Reality. And his  

190
00:15:43,680 --> 00:15:48,960
conceptualization for what it means to become an 
adult, what it means to go from being an infant  

191
00:15:48,960 --> 00:15:56,480
to a child to an adult is when you're first born, 
you're effectively fused with usually your mother,  

192
00:15:56,480 --> 00:16:02,160
your caregiver. There's no difference between 
you and her or you and whoever your caregiver is. 

193
00:16:02,160 --> 00:16:09,200
And growing up is this process of being gradually 
let down in certain moments where you can handle  

194
00:16:09,200 --> 00:16:14,240
being let down. So you learn that there's a 
separation between you and your caregiver. So  

195
00:16:14,240 --> 00:16:21,120
for infants, it's instead of being fused at the 
hip for every hour of every day, you get left  

196
00:16:21,120 --> 00:16:26,240
alone. Maybe you get left alone to cry it out. 
Who knows if that's the right thing to do with  

197
00:16:26,240 --> 00:16:32,320
infants? A lot of consternation there. But that's 
teaching you that there's a separation between  

198
00:16:32,320 --> 00:16:38,080
you and your mom or you and your dad. There's 
not going to always be someone to pick you up. 

199
00:16:38,080 --> 00:16:43,680
And raising a child is about knowing when 
they're ready to be let down a little bit  

200
00:16:43,680 --> 00:16:48,960
and have to stand up on their own. So I 
think there's that same leash with human  

201
00:16:48,960 --> 00:16:53,200
development. You get longer and longer 
periods of time where you can be on your  

202
00:16:53,200 --> 00:16:58,640
own. So we're still in the 20 to 30 minutes 
is maybe... I don't know, you probably can't  

203
00:16:58,640 --> 00:17:02,720
leave a toddler alone for 20 or 30 minutes, 
but it's a little bit older than a toddler.

204
00:17:02,720 --> 00:17:05,440
Maybe 20, 30 seconds.

205
00:17:06,720 --> 00:17:13,200
With a toddler, you can be in the same room but 
not interacting with them every single second  

206
00:17:14,240 --> 00:17:22,880
for 20 minutes sometimes. So it's around there. 
I think we have that similar leash with AGI. And  

207
00:17:22,880 --> 00:17:30,000
so I think a good definition of AGI is when does 
it become economically profitable for people to  

208
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:34,320
run agents indefinitely? So it just never turns 
off. It's a Claude Code that's always running,  

209
00:17:34,320 --> 00:17:37,760
it's always doing something, you just never 
turn it off, and you don't need to because  

210
00:17:38,400 --> 00:17:42,880
you know that it's worthwhile to keep it on.
It's never waiting for you to be like, "Okay,  

211
00:17:42,880 --> 00:17:45,520
next thing." It'll always respond to you 
when you're like, "Okay, next thing."  

212
00:17:45,520 --> 00:17:51,680
But it's off just essentially living its life 
like a teenager and that is profitable for you.  

213
00:17:51,680 --> 00:17:55,760
You'd rather have it do that than just 
wait for you to tell it what to do next.

214
00:17:55,760 --> 00:17:56,400
Interesting.

215
00:17:56,400 --> 00:17:58,400
I think that's a good definition of AGI.

216
00:17:58,400 --> 00:18:02,560
The profitable piece is also just the 
cost of running that thing and having it.

217
00:18:02,560 --> 00:18:07,280
It's partly the cost and partly the value. 
And obviously, you can game this a little bit  

218
00:18:07,280 --> 00:18:10,640
and be like, "Cool, I'm just going to tell 
Claude to run in a loop forever." But I'm  

219
00:18:10,640 --> 00:18:18,480
talking about more than that, more widespread 
adoption of agents that work all the time.  

220
00:18:19,040 --> 00:18:24,000
And I like the profitable thing, because 
if it costs a little bit of money and the  

221
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:29,280
bar is profitability, it has to actually be 
doing something useful for you to keep it on.

222
00:18:29,280 --> 00:18:36,160
It's interesting how the metaphor of 
a senior employee and autonomy and  

223
00:18:36,160 --> 00:18:39,360
essentially the more autonomous they are, 
the less instruction you have to give,  

224
00:18:39,360 --> 00:18:43,920
the less reviews you have to do, is also just 
directly correlated with how senior they are.

225
00:18:43,920 --> 00:18:44,960
Totally.

226
00:18:44,960 --> 00:18:48,160
Okay, great. Anything else along these lines?

227
00:18:48,160 --> 00:18:55,920
I have plenty of them. I hate the headlines that 
are like, "It's going to replace jobs," or "It's  

228
00:18:55,920 --> 00:19:00,720
going to unemploy two thirds of the workforce." 
I don't think that's true. I hate headlines that  

229
00:19:00,720 --> 00:19:06,720
are like, "You don't use your brain when you 
use ChatGPT," or another good headline is,  

230
00:19:09,280 --> 00:19:15,120
"Doctors alone, doctors plus AI, or just 
AI, which one is better? AI is better,  

231
00:19:15,120 --> 00:19:21,520
therefore, doctors are going to be outmoded."
All that stuff is, I think, pretty dumb.  

232
00:19:21,520 --> 00:19:29,680
So for the doctors plus AI example, I think it's 
important to recognize that using AI is a skill.  

233
00:19:29,680 --> 00:19:35,520
And so if you study doctors in a vacuum that 
don't really have a lot of experience with AI,  

234
00:19:35,520 --> 00:19:41,920
you could probably create a situation such that 
it's better to just use an AI. And sometimes it  

235
00:19:41,920 --> 00:19:46,960
is going to be better. But there's so many 
contexts that doctors need to make decisions  

236
00:19:46,960 --> 00:19:51,920
and do things that it's really hard to take 
one study and make any conclusion about that. 

237
00:19:51,920 --> 00:19:56,480
And it's especially hard when you're dealing with 
a technology that's developing so rapidly that  

238
00:19:56,480 --> 00:20:02,240
doctors can't really be expected to be experts 
at it yet. But I would guess in five or 10 years,  

239
00:20:02,240 --> 00:20:09,040
that will be totally and completely different. For 
the student example or the "AI turns your brain  

240
00:20:09,040 --> 00:20:17,680
off" example, I think it's really important to 
understand that in the history of technology, it  

241
00:20:17,680 --> 00:20:22,800
has always been the case that you give up certain 
skills in order to get other ones. For example,  

242
00:20:22,800 --> 00:20:29,040
Plato is famously very skeptical of writing 
because he thought it would harm your memory.  

243
00:20:29,040 --> 00:20:34,080
And it did. We don't remember things quite as well 
as they did back in the day because they had to  

244
00:20:34,080 --> 00:20:39,520
remember long epic poems to entertain each other.
But I think writing is a worthwhile trade for  

245
00:20:39,520 --> 00:20:42,800
having a slightly worse memory. And I 
think something similar is going on with  

246
00:20:43,520 --> 00:20:50,080
AI where you may be slightly less engaged 
in certain tasks, but if you use it right,  

247
00:20:50,080 --> 00:20:55,680
you're going to be way more engaged in other tasks 
where you have much more power. And so you can  

248
00:20:55,680 --> 00:21:00,960
construct a study that says brain connectivity 
goes down when you use AI in the same way that  

249
00:21:00,960 --> 00:21:06,240
you could construct a study that says people's 
memory are worse when they have writing skills.  

250
00:21:06,240 --> 00:21:09,920
But I don't think anyone would want to go 
back to a world where no one was literate.

251
00:21:09,920 --> 00:21:14,480
That is super interesting. There's all these 
studies that are showing the benefits of AI  

252
00:21:14,480 --> 00:21:20,080
to students with these studies in Nigeria and 
just how fast people progress. So I think it's  

253
00:21:20,080 --> 00:21:22,720
really important, this context you're 
sharing that you will lose some things,  

254
00:21:22,720 --> 00:21:26,960
but the hope is the gain is much higher, 
and so far it seems like it will be.

255
00:21:26,960 --> 00:21:31,040
Yeah. I think people always, especially 
at the beginning of a tech hype cycle or  

256
00:21:31,040 --> 00:21:34,640
a revolution paradigm shift, it's always 
easy to underestimate how quickly things  

257
00:21:34,640 --> 00:21:40,960
